      <div class='hentry member_contribution' id='S5LV0656P0-03882'>
        <a name='S5LV0656P0_20040203_GCR_145'>  </a>
        <blockquote cite='http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/people/mr-john-whitty' class='contribution_text entry-content'>
          <a class='speech-permalink permalink' href='#S5LV0656P0_20040203_GCR_145' title='Link to this speech by Mr John Whitty' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
          <cite class='member author entry-title'><a href="/people/mr-john-whitty" title="Mr John Whitty">Lord Whitty</a></cite>
          <p class='first-para'>
            I would not encourage the noble Duke or the Scottish Parliament to extend the Scottish
            <a class='permalink column-permalink' id='column_328gc' title='Col. 328GC &mdash; HL Deb 03 February 2004 vol 656 c328GC' name='column_328gc' href='#column_328gc' rel='bookmark'>328GC</a>
            hegemony over any wider an area than it already has. The point is that the designation of the areas is a UK responsibility because the waters beyond that area belong to the UK. But the enforcement of certain aspects of environmental protection, for example, will fall to Scottish Ministers and agencies. This clause deals only with the delineation, which is clearly a UK power.
          </p>
        </blockquote>
      </div>
      
      <div class='hentry member_contribution' id='S5LV0656P0-03883'>
        <a name='S5LV0656P0_20040203_GCR_146'>  </a>
        <blockquote cite='http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/people/mr-james-graham-3' class='contribution_text entry-content'>
